A man has been stabbed to death in Leeds with a murder investigation launched by police. Three streets in the Chapeltown area of the city were cordoned after the victim's death today (March 2).  The police were called by paramedics at 2.39pm to reports of a man with serious stab injuries. He was taken to hospital, but died of his injuries, according to West Yorkshire Police. A cordon has covered Hamilton Avenue, Spencer Place and Rossington Drive in Chapeltown. A spokesperson for West Yorkshire Police said the force has launched a murder investigation after the stabbing.  They added: "Police were called by the ambulance service at 2.39pm to a report a man had been located there with serious stab injuries. "He was taken to hospital but sadly died there from his injuries. "Scenes are currently in place at locations including Hamilton Avenue, Spencer Place and Rossington Drive as officers conduct initial enquires into what took place." The force has issued an appeal for witnesses or anyone with information to come forward. READ ABOUT MEGHAN AND HARRY BEING ACCUSED OF 'SCROUNGING'  Contact the Homicide and Major Enquiry Team on 101 referencing police log 909 of March 2. Information can also be given online at westyorkshire.police.uk/101livechat or anonymously to the independent charity Crimestoppers on 0800 555 111. DON'T MISS: SNP MP told to apologise over â€˜ignorant racial slur' [REVEALED] Mum praised for transforming son into Prince Harry on World Book Day [REPORT] 'I queued an hour to visit Clarkson's farm shop but was underwhelmed' [OPINION]